##Before the new crown outbreak, the disease control system was in crisis

Micro signal

What happened before the Earth was destroyed?

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
By Han Fang Hang

Editor | Kylin Zhu

Since the outbreak of COVID-19 pneumonia, the CDC, which is supposed to be responsible for disease control and Response to public health emergencies, has been thrust into the spotlight by a seemingly "well-known" paper. The paper, signed by several CDC officials, notes that human to human transmission has been occurring in the COVID-19 since mid December 2019. Earlier, several experts in China's health system had denied human-to-human transmission in the early stages of the epidemic.

On the afternoon of January 31st, Takatomi, the CDC's director, and Feng Zijian, its deputy director, each offered an oblique response, suggesting that they were part of a complex process of "alerting the public to the outbreak. ". And what we're trying to figure out is, what is the CDC, what is the role of the CDC?

After combing through the reports on China's Disease Control System in recent years, we found that the internal of the disease control system for its own decline seems to have been early warning. Large staff losses and financial shortfalls may leave the CDC unable to play its proper role in controlling the spread of disease in the event of a sudden outbreak.

"facing the grand goal of 'healthy China 2030' , it should be a good opportunity for public health and the development of the disease control and prevention system. When China's Disease Control and Prevention people shed their arms, but because of long-standing problems and the impact of the recent drop in income due to policy reasons, the disease control and prevention system fluctuated and the brain drain accelerated. " June 2019, zeng Guang, a researcher at the Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention, said at a ten-year seminar on China's health care reform held by the Development Research Center of the State Council.

Zeng's message is intended to appeal to China to pay more attention to the role of the CDC in healthcare reform and to play its due role. To make the disease control system play its due role, it also depends on the correction of many institutional problems in China's disease control system.

The brain drain is the most obvious problem facing China's disease control system. This brain drain occurs at all levels, from the central to the local. During the two sessions in 2019, he lin, deputy director of the Health Promotion and education institute at the Guizhou Provincial Center for Disease Control and Prevention, cited the central level Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention as an example, pointing out that the Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention had 165 employees between 2015 and 2017, two of them are one billion national level talent candidates, outstanding contribution experts, government special paste experts top experts. In 2018 another 49 people, "a direct impact on the national CDC core competitiveness, impact on the future development of disease control. " [3]

Shanghai, a first-tier city, is not optimistic either. Shanghai Public Health Clinical Center was established in 2004 after SARS, referring to Beijing's Xiaotangshan Model, as an infectious disease centralized admission and treatment isolation point. The same is true in the case of COVID-19. 2007-9-2415:00[ hide ] however, the hospital is also facing a severe brain drain.

In an interview with Zhu Tongyu, a member of the Standing Committee of the Shanghai Municipal Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference, in January 2017, the paper pointed out that, "In the past five years, the turnover rate of frontline staff in the Shanghai Public Health Clinical Center has remained high, with 205 medical staff leaving the hospital, accounting for 23.3 percent of the hospital's staff. Twenty-three percent of those who lost their jobs were doctors... at present, there are backbone to apply for departure, especially the clinical backbone of the departure of the Public Health Center caused incalculable losses, seriously weakened the Public Health Center to Infectious Disease Epidemic Emergency Response Capacity, once the outbreak of the epidemic, will not be able to afford the basic treatment tasks

In addition, Health News, an organ under the China National Health and Health Commission, Interviewed Party Secretaries and directors of several local health and health committees during the two sessions in March 2019. Officials from Jilin, Inner Mongolia, Guangxi and other places all agreed that, "there is a clear talent gap in disease control and prevention institutions, a shortage of public health doctors and a shortage of special local disease prevention and control personnel. " Among them, Jilin Province also has an aging trend of disease control and prevention staff, "At the city and county level, the age structure of the staff is mainly in the 45-54 age group, and the proportion is increasing year by year. ". [6]

At present, China's Disease Control System personnel gap is very obvious. The United Front and the Chinese Peasants'and Workers'Democratic Party submitted a proposal during the 2019 Shanghai Municipal People's Congress to strengthen the ranks of public health professionals in Shanghai. One set of data is alarming.

"The staffing of the CDC is in accordance with the requirements of the Central Administration and is in principle approved in accordance with the proportion of 1.75 per 10,000 of Shanghai's permanent population. At the end of 2017, Shanghai's permanent population was 24,183,300. In theory, the total number of CDC staff required is 4,232. In fact, according to the Shanghai Center for Disease Control and Prevention in 2017, the city's total number of CDC staff is 2,904, the staffing gap is still 1,328."[7]

At that rate, China's population of 1.4 billion would need about 245,000 disease control workers, compared with about 200,000, or nearly 20 percent, according to the report by he lin.

The reason for the brain drain in the CDC system is probably the same as in other industries, the lack of job satisfaction and the lack of economic returns, both of which are related to institutional changes.

From the economic perspective, we check a number of local CDC department balance sheets found that the disease control system can obtain financial support is not stable. In recent years, the CDC budget in some areas has increased, but there are also a number of CDC budget has declined significantly.

The Yunnan Provincial Center for Disease Control and Prevention had a combined revenue of 514 million yuan in 2017, leaving 448 million yuan in 2018. Of this total, the allocation from the government budget fell from 351 million yuan to 339 million yuan. [8] the annual revenue of the Tianjin Center for Disease Control and prevention was 228 million yuan in 2018,148 million yuan less than in 2017. 2007-9-2415:00[ hide ] the same situation has been found in Ngawa Tibetan and Qiang Autonomous Prefecture, Heze, Changsha and Tianxin, Hunan.

Since SARS in 2003, funding for the CDC system has increased in absolute terms, but has not kept pace with overall economic development. According to a report in the Guangming Daily, "The ratio of government input to fiscal expenditure at the same level has shown a downward trend, from 1.27 per 1,000 in 2002 to 1.05 per 1,000 in 2012, a drop of 17.3 per cent. The growth of government input lags behind the growth rate of the social economy. " [10]

In addition, the Guangming Daily pointed out that the funds obtained by the CDC system are more used for specific projects in the specific category of prevention and control, while the regular maintenance funds, which are essential for maintaining public functions, are still insufficient. "In 2002-2012, per capita expenditure on personnel increased by 290.6 percent, and per capita expenditure on public utilities increased by 190.8 percent... Both were lower than the national fiscal expenditure (471.1 percent) and the growth rate of the social economy (308.8 percent) during the same period, " which led to insufficient economic incentives for employees in the CDC system. Some places even can not complete the routine infectious disease epidemic prevention function.

In addition to insufficient financial input, in recent years, CDC reform measures have further tightened the financial resources of the CDC. In China's current system, CDC belongs to Public Welfare Institutions. But until now, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention received part of its revenue from payments to the public, such as health checks and vaccinations. In 2017, the State Council ordered the removal of some administrative fees. The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention has also been affected, and some fee items have been canceled. People who pay for second-class vaccinations are also required not to pay a premium for the service on top of the price of the vaccine. All this has had an impact on the CDC's revenue.

The Yongxiu County Center for Disease Control and Prevention in Jiujiang, Jiangxi Province, pointed out in its 2018 departmental final accounts that, "In 2018, the revenue of the Department of the Yongxiu County Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) is estimated to be $8.547 million, a decrease of $2.2155 million from the previous year's budget, due to the abolition of various fee items and the zero price differential for vaccines. " [11]

Zeng Guang believes that although the CDC should abolish excessive administrative fees to fulfill the CDC's public welfare functions, if this part of income is not immediately covered by financial resources, it will also dampen the enthusiasm of CDC employees, and further loss of personnel.

Such concerns are not misplaced. When first finance was investigating the grey industry chain of second-class vaccines, it cited experts WHO worked at the WHO's Center for Immunization Planning, "In a county-level epidemic prevention station in Hebei Province, there are more than 50 people, only 12 of whom are on the staff. The rest of the people's wages need to be found through the market. If they cut off the benefits of the vaccine, they will look for other ways to make money. But without these temporary workers, preventive work can not be done by the staff alone."[12] A local CDC staff said, "If we do not rely on business income, we can not give no staff salaries. "

The Jiangsu Provincial Center for Disease Control and Prevention published an article in the August 2018 issue of China Health Policy Research. After surveying 102 Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, they concluded, "after the abolition of administrative fees... only 16% of the institutions have government compensation, some institutions have staff income decline, staff outflow departments or units, equipment replacement and maintenance affected. " [13]

In the case of a large staff loss, lack of financial allocation, there are signs that the importance of the disease control system is further reduced. In 2018, two provinces, Shanxi and Liaoning, launched a new round of institutional reforms, and county-and city-level Centers for Disease Control and Prevention have even lost their status as an independent agency.

On July 4,2018, Shenyang released the "optimization and integration plan for Public Welfare practice units in Shenyang City" . The Shenyang Center for Disease Control and Prevention was merged into the municipal center for Health Services and administrative law enforcement, which is an institution affiliated to the Municipal Health and Family Planning Commission, indefinite mechanism specification. Also belonging to the center of institutions, the center blood station, blood donation office, Medical Service Center, Health Education Center and other institutions.

A week earlier, Fushun announced a similar restructuring plan. Fushun CDC integrated into the city's Big Health Industry Research Institute, a municipal directly affiliated institutions, institutions at the county level. Also belong to the Industry Research Institute of institutions, primary and secondary health care, central blood station, Emergency Command Center, Medical Association and other institutions. [14]

In Shanxi, Feng Lizhong, deputy director of the Shanxi Provincial Health and Family Planning Commission and Director of the provincial medical reform office, said that by the end of August 2018,24 model counties will integrate the centers into the medical group. [15]

This has been interpreted as a further weakening of the CDC. "The government and administration have not paid enough attention to preventive medicine and public health, neglected the construction of the CDC's Public Health Team, resulting in poor treatment, the loss of the best talent, and even some local programs that have either eliminated the CDC or merged it with hospitals, " Zhang Zuofeng, associate dean of UCLA's public health and a senior tenured professor of epidemiology, told the intellectuals

In fact, in the past few years, the disease control system has been weakened, unable to play its due to the prevention and treatment of infectious diseases are already signs. For example, in the 2009 influenza a (H1N1) epidemic, from 11 May 2009 to 10 August 2010, a total of 128033 cases were confirmed in mainland China, resulting in 805 deaths and a fatality rate of 0.6% . [17]

Hand-foot-mouth disease (HFMD) has re-emerged as a major public health threat in China since 2007. According to a paper published in 2019 in the Chinese Journal of Epidemiology, from 2008 to 2017, the reported incidence rate of hand-foot-mouth disease (HFMD) in China was 134.59 per 100,000, an average increase of 15.92% , and the proportion of severe cases reported was 0.84% , an average increase of 9.56% . [18]

In these cases, China's Disease Control and prevention system does not seem to be fulfilling the responsibilities assigned to it. The data presented above point to the external pressures facing many disease control systems. Due to the long-term lack of attention to infectious disease prevention and control, resulting in the lack of funds for the disease control system, brain drain. And when the COVID-19 hit, the disease control system was in retreat, just as it had been seen.

A holistic review of the disease control system, including its internal mechanisms of operation and its relationship to the bureaucracy as a whole, is still necessary. And what this article is trying to point out is that if a country has to have an agency that takes on the role of disease prevention and control, and that role now needs to be taken on by the CDC, then the position and role of this institution in the health care system must be further strengthened. Whether it is a scientific institution or a policy enforcer, more resources and a voice are needed if the next pandemic is to be contained.
